StringLiteralExpr.value: freezeColors allows multiple colormaps to be used per figure.
As this is a graphics function, you will have to use your eyes to verify
correct behavior. In addition, no errors should be reported.
First, An image is drawn, using the hot colormap.
>> imagesc(peaks); axis xy; colormap hot; title(''colors not frozen''); colorbar
Next, if we change the colormap to jet, the plot will change appearance.
Now, repeat the plot, but using freezeColors. We also freeze the colorbar,
using the function cbfreeze by Carlos Adrian Vargas Aguilera. Note: this
function must be downloaded separately from the MATLAB Central File Exchange!
cbfreeze is not available, so colorbar colors will not be frozen until you
go and download it from the file exchange. Sorry for the extra step, but
it is necessary because of matlab internal changes. Please visit
>> imagesc(p); axis xy; colormap jet; title(''jet colormap, frozen'')
>> cbfreeze %NOTE: this is separately available from File Exchange
The two plots should appear identical.
However, if we now change the colormap again, this time to cool, the left
plot should change but the frozen one on the right will remain the same.
This shows that freezeColor is working as intended because the frozen
plot is no longer affected by the colormap.
Next, test some other plot types (image, scatter, bar, surf), as well as
correct handling of NaNs in images. You will see a variety of plots,
using a variety of different colormaps--all on the same figure.
Finally, test unfreezeColors by unfreezing the entire figure, after
All plots are restored to the unfrozen state and are once again
